The paper discusses a new approach to software-defined networking for wireless networks, which involves generating distributed cross-layer control programs based on distributed optimization theory. This falls under the category of network optimization and control, which is typically covered in the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of optimization algorithms to generate solution algorithms for subproblems, which could also fall under the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of a centralized abstraction to control the global network behavior, which could fall under the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of a new Wireless Network Operating System (WNOS), which could fall under the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses experimental results, which could fall under the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
